The stock is exactly like one found on standard Type 56 carbines only the magazine well has a steel sleeve and is enlarged accept the larger magazine. title: For Sale:  Marlin xl7
postcontent:
marlin 30-06  with sling , 3x9x50 scope, and 60 rounds of ammo.

this  is  great 30-06 rifle  very smooth bolt action holds 4 rounds & 1 in  chamber. shot 16 rounds through it. great deer gun.
and a pro fire trigger system. The Pro-Fire trigger system has an articulating trigger-release lever that moves through a slot in the trigger bow and will not allow the trigger rearward until it is depressed. Parts are housed in an alloy casting, and sear engagement and overtravel are preset by the component’s geometry. Pull weight is adjusted by first loosening a jam nut on a threaded set screw protruding from the front of the housing and then turning the set screw either in or out with an Allen-head wrench.

Turning the set screw in will increase the pull weight, and turning the set screw out reduces the pull weight. The pull weight ranges from can-hardly-make-it-go-off heavy to 2 1/2 pounds, where the unit bottoms out. Triggers come from the factory preset at 3 1/2 pounds.
It has never been used  other than zero in scope.  its the smoothest bolt action I have shot.

Read more: http://www.shootingtimes.com/2011/01/03/longgun_reviews_st_marlinxl7_200804/#ixzz2jYDr7lkp

title: For Sale:  .45 For the common man
postcontent: This is an unusual piece, the Ballester Molina. I'll save you some time on google. in this condition stock these are $350-425 guns however you are about to find out this one is anything but stock. This .45 is based off and resembles the colt 1911 however is not a clone. No grip safety and some parts are different. The parts that are in common are the barrel, link guide and spring, bushing and the magazine. All of which have been replaced and upgraded with superior quality parts. These include a colt mil spec barrel part number 7791193, ED Brown stainless 2 pc. guide rod, ED brown stainless bushing and recoil spring and a McCormick "shooting star" 8rd mag. The parts that are not shared with the colt are obtainable via the web. This gun is all steel and will be still around in another 75 years (the serial numbers which all match put it in 1944-45 year production) and function just as it does now. The slide is smooth and affirmative, unlike some modern Far eastern imports. The ejection port has been lowered and scalloped (popular on high end 1911's to enhance ejection and ensure optimal reliability) the work being well done and tasteful. I bought this as a project and now its time for me to move on. The only thing it could use is a more modern set of grips which are available reasonably from a number of retailers.
